snippet.textDisplay:
No! Wilder shouldn't opt in for immediate rematch with Tyson Fury. What went wrong is the habit not learning (or taking serious) the basic fundamentals of boxing: ducking; countering; head movement; anticipation; footwork; feints; blocking.

Even at heavyweight they should be sound in the basic skills of a boxer.

If I could I would ask Wilder if Fury held a sword in his hands: would he just stand cement footed? Would he not bob and weave, try to slip and duck? Would he not try to counter and make every strike counts? Would he not use footwork to move out the way, try to change direction? I would ask Wilder would he care how ugly he looks while trying to keep from getting sliced and chopped in two? He should be the same way in taking serious mastering the basics of boxing. Especially vs Tyson Fury.

Wilder shouldn't exercise rematch clause until he has improved in the fundamentals.

Boxer & trainer IQ also is to understand or perceive what worked vs other opponents will not or may not work vs another. When fighter cannot see this then the trainers should.

Versus other top opponents Wilder may not need to be accurate. But in rematch vs Fury he cannot afford it. Versus other opponents in future Wilder may not need to worry about countering, footwork, ring generalship. But vs Fury he now has to understand and apply it. Versus other opponents Wilder may not have to take head movement, slipping punches, defense seriously. But in rematch vs Fury he will need to.

Congratulations to Tyson Fury especially his team. He overcame a lot.

I'm just a casual boxing fan. A nobody. Just an opinion.
